VToday I want to talk about the meaning of words,
p4
aVhow we define them
p5
aVand how they, almost as revenge,
p6
aVdefine us.
p7
aa(lp8
VThe English language is a magnificent sponge.
p9
aVI love the English language. I'm glad that I speak it.
p10
aVBut for all that, it has a lot of holes.
p11
aVIn Greek, there's a word, "lachesism"
p12
aVwhich is the hunger for disaster.
p13
aVYou know, when you see a thunderstorm on the horizon
p14
aVand you just find yourself rooting for the storm.
p15
aVIn Mandarin, they have a word "yù y\u012b" \u2014
p16
aVI'm not pronouncing that correctly \u2014
p17
aVwhich means the longing to feel intensely again
p18
aVthe way you did when you were a kid.
p19
aVIn Polish, they have a word "jouska"
p20
aVwhich is the kind of hypothetical conversation
p21
aVthat you compulsively play out in your head.
p22
aVAnd finally, in German, of course in German,
p23
aVthey have a word called "zielschmerz"
p24
aVwhich is the dread of getting what you want.
p25
aa(lp26
V(Laughter)
p27
aa(lp28
VFinally fulfilling a lifelong dream.
p29
aVI'm German myself, so I know exactly what that feels like.
p30
aa(lp31
VNow, I'm not sure if I would use any of these words
p32
aVas I go about my day,
p33
aVbut I'm really glad they exist.
p34
aVBut the only reason they exist is because I made them up.
p35
aa(lp36
VI am the author of "The Dictionary of Obscure Sorrows,"
p37
aVwhich I've been writing for the last seven years.
p38
aVAnd the whole mission of the project
p39
aVis to find holes in the language of emotion
p40
aVand try to fill them
p41
aVso that we have a way of talking about all those human peccadilloes
p42
aVand quirks of the human condition
p43
aVthat we all feel but may not think to talk about
p44
aVbecause we don't have the words to do it.
p45
aa(lp46
VAnd about halfway through this project,
p47
aVI defined "sonder,"
p48
aVthe idea that we all think of ourselves as the main character
p49
aVand everyone else is just extras.
p50
aVBut in reality, we're all the main character,
p51
aVand you yourself are an extra in someone else's story.
p52
aVAnd so as soon as I published that,
p53
aVI got a lot of response from people
p54
aVsaying, "Thank you for giving voice to something I had felt all my life
p55
aVbut there was no word for that."
p56
aVSo it made them feel less alone.
p57
aVThat's the power of words,
p58
aVto make us feel less alone.
p59
aa(lp60
VAnd it was not long after that
p61
aVthat I started to notice sonder
p62
aVbeing used earnestly in conversations online,
p63
aVand not long after I actually noticed it,
p64
aVI caught it next to me in an actual conversation in person.
p65
aVThere is no stranger feeling than making up a word
p66
aVand then seeing it take on a mind of its own.
p67
aVI don't have a word for that yet, but I will.
p68
aa(lp69
V(Laughter)
p70
aa(lp71
VI'm working on it.
